name: Peter
text: Converted Jew. Apostle of Jesus. According to Catholic tradition he received the keys of the Kingdom of Heaven (Matthew 16:18–19). Feast day (Feast of Saints Peter and Paul) 29 June, (Chair of Saint Peter) 22 February. He is recognized by the Catholic Church as the first Bishop of Rome appointed by Christ. Also revered as saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 29 June.[4] The St. Peter's Basilica in Vatican City is named after him.

name: Linus
text: First Roman pope.[5] Feast day 23 September. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 7 June.

name: Anacletus
text: Historicity not proven. First Greek pope. Feast day 26 April. Once erroneously split into Cletus and Anacletus.[6]

name: Clement I
text: Roman. Feast day 23 November. Issued 1 Clement which is said to be the basis of apostolic authority for the clergy. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 25 November. First Pope to abdicate

name: Evaristus
text:
Converted Jew. Said to have divided Rome into parishes, assigning
                                a priest to each. Feast day of 26 October.

name: Alexander I
text: Roman. Inaugurated the custom of blessing houses with holy water. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 18 March.

name: Sixtus I
text: Roman. Feast day of 6 April. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 10 August.

name: Telesphorus
text: Greek. Feast day of 5 January. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 22 February. Church Father St. Irenaeus called him a great martyr.

name: Hyginus
text: Greek. Tradition holds he was martyred; feast day 11 January.

name: Pius I
text: Roman. Martyred by sword; feast day 11 July. Decreed that Easter should only be celebrated on a Sunday.

name: Anicetus
text: Greek. First pope from Syria. Tradition holds he was martyred; feast day 17 April. Decreed that priests are not allowed to have long hair.

name: Soter
text:
Roman. Tradition holds he was martyred; feast day 22 April.
                                Declared that marriage was valid as a sacrament blessed by a priest; formally
                                inaugurated Easter as an annual festival in Rome.

name: Eleuterus
text: Greek. Tradition holds he was martyred; feast day 6 May.

name: Victor I
text: Roman. Known for excommunicating Theodotus of Byzantium. Quartodecimanism controversy.

name: Zephyrinus
text:
Roman. Combated against the adoptionist heresies of the followers of Theodotus the Byzantium who were ruled by Theodotus, the Money Changer and Asclepiodotus.

Although not physically martyred (murdered), he is called a martyr for the suffering he endured.

name: Callixtus I
text: Roman. Martyred; feast day 14 October.

name: Urban I
text: Roman. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 25 May.

name: Pontian
text: Roman. First to abdicate after exile to Sardinia by Emperor Maximinus Thrax. The Liberian Catalogue records his death on 28 Sept 235, the earliest exact date in papal history.[8][9]

name: Anterus
text: Greek. Feast day 3 January. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 5 August.

name: Fabian
text: Roman. Divided the communities of Rome into seven districts, each supervised by a deacon. Feast day 20 January. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 5 August.

name: Cornelius
text:
Roman. Died as a martyr through extreme hardship; feast day 16
                                September.

name: Lucius I
text: Roman. Feast day 5 March.

name: Stephen I
text: Greek Roman. Martyred by beheading; feast day 2 August. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with the same feast day.

name: Sixtus II
text: Greek. Martyred by beheading. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 10 August.

name: Dionysius
text: Greek. Feast day 26 December.

name: Felix I
text: Roman.

name: Eutychian
text: Roman.

name: Caius
text: Greek. First pope from Croatia. Martyred by beheading (according to legend). Feast day 22 April. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 11 August.

name: Marcellinus
text: Roman. Feast day 26 April. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 7 June.

name: Marcellus I
text: Roman. Banished from Rome under Maxentius (309).

name: Eusebius
text: Greek. Banished by the emperor Maxentius, and died in exile.

name: Miltiades
text: Roman. First pope after the end of the persecution of Christians through the Edict of Milan (313 AD) issued by Constantine the Great. Presided over the Lateran council of 313.

name: Sylvester I
text: Roman. Feast day 31 December. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 2 January. First Council of Nicaea (325). Under him was built: the Basilica of St. John Lateran, Santa Croce in Gerusalemme and Old St. Peter's Basilica. Donation of Constantine.

name: Mark
text:
Roman. One of Mark's undertakings was to compile stories of the
                                lives of martyrs and bishops before his time. There is some reason to believe he founded
                                two churches in the area of Rome. One of them is still known to this day as the Church
                                of San Marco, although it is greatly changed since his time. The other church was at the
                                Catacomb of Balbina, a cemetery. Emperor Constantine gave gifts of land and furnishing
                                for both buildings. Feast day 7 October.

name: Julius I
text: Roman. Arian controversy. Credited with splitting the birth of Christ into two distinct celebrations: The Epiphany stayed on the traditional date, and the Nativity was added on 25 December.

name: Liberius
text: Roman. Earliest pope not canonized by the Roman Catholic Church. Revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 27 August.[10]

name: Damasus I
text: Roman. And the first pope from Portugal. Patron of Jerome, commissioned the Vulgate translation of the Bible. Council of Rome (382).

name: Siricius
text: Roman. His famous letters—the earliest surviving texts of papal decretals—focus particularly on religious discipline and include decisions on baptism, consecration, ordination, penance, and continence. Siricius’ important decretal of 386 (written to Bishop Himerius of Tarragona), commanding celibacy for priests, was the first decree on this subject.[11]

name: Anastasius I
text: Roman. Instructed priests to stand and bow their heads as they read from the Gospels.

name: Innocent I
text: Roman. Visigoth Sack of Rome (410) under Alaric.

name: Zosimus
text: Greek.

name: Boniface I
text: Roman.

name: Celestine I
text: Greek. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 8 April.

name: Sixtus III
text: Roman.

name: Leo I
text: Roman. Convinced Attila the Hun to turn back his invasion of Italy. Wrote the Tome which was instrumental in the Council of Chalcedon and in defining the hypostatic union. Feast day 10 November. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 18 February.

name: Hilarius
text: Greek.

name: Simplicius
text: Roman. Papacy during the collapse of the Western Roman Empire and subsequent overtaking of Rome and Italy in general by Odoacer.

name: Felix III
text:
Roman. Sometimes called Felix II. Great-great-grandfather of pope
                                Gregory I.

name: Gelasius I
text: Greek. The last pope to have been born on the continent of Africa. The first pope called the "Vicar of Christ".[12]

name: Anastasius II
text: Roman. Tried to end the Acacian schism but it resulted in the Laurentian schism.

name: Symmachus
text: Greek.

name: Hormisdas
text: Roman. Father of Pope Silverius. Acacian schism.

name: John I
text: Roman.

name: Felix IV
text: Roman. Sometimes called Felix III. Built Santi Cosma e Damiano.

name: Boniface II
text: Roman. Changed the numbering of the years in the Julian Calendar from Ab Urbe Condita to Anno Domini.

name: John II
text: Roman. First pope not to use his personal name. This was because of the Roman god, Mercury.

name: Agapetus I
text: Roman. Feast days 22 April and 20 September. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 17 April.

name: Silverius
text: Roman. Exiled; feast day 20 June, son of Pope Hormisdas.

name: Vigilius
text: Roman.

name: Pelagius I
text: Roman. Credited with the construction of the basilica of Santi Apostoli.

name: John III
text: Roman.

name: Benedict I
text: Roman.

name: Pelagius II
text: Roman (probably of Ostrogothic descent). Ordered the construction of the Basilica di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura.

name: Gregory I
text: Last imperial Roman Pope. Great-great-grandson of pope Felix III. The first formally to employ the titles Servus servorum Dei and Pontifex Maximus. Established the Gregorian chant. Feast day 3 September. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 12 March. Known as "the Father of Christian Worship". Known as "St. Gregory the Dialogist" in Eastern Orthodoxy.

name: Sabinian
text: Greek. For the next two centuries the Roman popes were all controlled by the Eastern Roman Empire.

name: Boniface III
text: Roman.

name: Boniface IV
text: Roman. First pope to bear the same name as his immediate predecessor. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Adeodatus I
text: Roman. Sometimes called Deusdedit, as a result Pope Adeodatus II is sometimes called Pope Adeodatus without a number. The first pope to use lead seals on papal documents, which in time came to be called Papal bulls.

name: Boniface V
text: Greek.

name: Honorius I
text: Greek. Named a heretic and anathematized by the Third Council of Constantinople. (680)

name: Severinus
text: Roman.

name: John IV
text: Greek. Second pope from Croatia.

name: Theodore I
text: Greek. The last pope from Palestine. Planned the Lateran Council of 649, but died before it could open.

name: Martin I
text: Roman. Last pope recognized as a martyr. Feast day of 12 November. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 14 April.

name: Eugene I
text: Roman.

name: Vitalian
text: Roman.

name: Adeodatus II
text: Roman. Sometimes called Pope Adeodatus (without a number) in reference to Pope Adeodatus I sometimes being called Pope Deusdedit. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Donus
text: Roman.

name: Agatho
text: Greek. The oldest pope in history. Also revered as a saint in Eastern Christianity, with a feast day of 20 February.

name: Leo II
text: Greek. Feast day 3 July.

name: Benedict II
text: Roman. Feast day 7 May.

name: John V
text: Greek.

name: Conon
text: Greek.

name: Sergius I
text: Greek. Introduced the singing of the Lamb of God at mass.[12]

name: John VI
text: Greek. The only pope came from Asia Minor.

name: John VII
text:
Greek.The second pope to bear the same name as his immediate
                                predecessor.

name: Sisinnius
text: Greek.

name: Constantine
text: Greek. Last pope to visit Greece while in office, until John Paul II in 2001.

name: Gregory II
text: Roman. Feast day 11 February. Held the Synod of Rome (721).

name: Gregory III
text: Greek. The last pope from Syria. The third pope to bear the same name as his immediate predecessor. Was previously the last pope to have been born outside Europe until the election of Francis in 2013.

name: Zachary
text: Greek. Feast day 15 March. Built the church of Santa Maria sopra Minerva.

name: Stephen II
text: Roman. Sometimes called Stephen III. The Donation of Pepin. Brother of Paul I.

name: Paul I
text: Roman. Brother of Stephen II.

name: Stephen III
text: Greek. Sometimes called Stephen IV. The Lateran Council (769).

name: Adrian I
text: Roman.

name: Leo III
text: Greek (From a modest family from southern Italy). Crowned Charlemagne Imperator Augus on Christmas Day, 800, thereby initiating what would become the office of Holy Roman Emperor requiring the imprimatur of the pope for its legitimacy.

name: Stephen IV
text: Early Italian. Sometimes called Stephen V.

name: Paschal I
text: Italian. Credited with finding the body of Saint Cecilia in the Catacomb of Callixtus, building the basilica of Santa Cecilia in Trastevere and the church of Santa Maria in Domnica.

name: Eugene II
text: Italian.

name: Valentine
text: Italian.

name: Gregory IV
text: Italian. Rebuilt the atrium of St. Peter’s Basilica and in the newly decorated chapel transferred the body of Gregory I.

name: Sergius II
text: Italian.

name: Leo IV
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Benedict III
text: Italian.

name: Nicholas I
text: Italian. Encouraged missionary activity.

name: Adrian II
text: Italian.

name: John VIII
text: Italian. First pope to be assassinated.

name: Marinus I
text: Italian. Sometimes also known as and called "Martin II."

name: Adrian III
text:
Italian. Feast day 8 July. Maybe the pope Adrian I was his
                                ancestor.

name: Stephen V
text: Italian. Sometimes called Stephen VI.

name: Formosus
text: Italian. Posthumously ritually executed following the Cadaver Synod.

name: Boniface VI
text: Italian.

name: Stephen VI
text: Italian. Sometimes called Stephen VII. Held the infamous Cadaver Synod.

name: Romanus
text: Italian.

name: Theodore II
text: Italian.

name: John IX
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Benedict IV
text: Italian.

name: Leo V
text: Italian. Deposed and murdered.

name: Sergius III
text: Italian. "Saeculum obscurum" begins. The first pope to be depicted with the Papal Tiara.

name: Anastasius III
text: Italian.

name: Lando
text: Italian.

name: John X
text: Italian.

name: Leo VI
text: Italian.

name: Stephen VII
text: Italian. Sometimes called Stephen VIII.

name: John XI
text: Italian. Probably, according to the Liber Pontificalis and Liutprand of Cremona, the son of Pope Sergius III, and not of Alberic I of Spoleto, who was Marozia's husband.

name: Leo VII
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Stephen VIII
text: Italian. Sometimes called Stephen IX.

name: Marinus II
text: Italian.

name: Agapetus II
text: Italian.

name: John XII
text: Italian. Third Pope not to use his personal name, after John II and John III. Deposed in 963 by Emperor Otto invalidly; end of the "Saeculum obscurum".

name: John XII
text: Italian. Murdered in 964.

name: Benedict V
text: Italian. Elected by the people of Rome, in opposition to the Antipope Leo VIII who was appointed by Emperor Otto; he accepted his own deposition in 964 leaving Leo VIII as the sole pope.

name: Leo VIII
text: Italian. Became the true pope after Benedict V was deposed, after being antipope from 963 to 964, in opposition to Pope John XII and Pope Benedict V. An appointee of the Holy Roman Emperor, Otto I, his pontificate occurred during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.

name: John XIII
text: Italian. Chronicled after his death as "the Good".

name: Benedict VI
text: Italian. Deposed and murdered.

name: Benedict VII
text:
Italian

.

name: John XIV
text: Italian. Fourth Pope not to use his personal name, after John II, John III and John XII.

name: John XV
text: Italian. The first pope to formally canonize a saint.

name: Gregory V
text:
The first German Pope and fifth not to use his personal name.
                                Henceforth, this decision became tradition among future popes.

name: Sylvester II
text: The first French pope.

name: John XVII
text: Italian.

name: John XVIII
text: Italian.

name: Sergius IV
text: Italian.

name: Benedict VIII
text: Italian.

name: John XIX
text: Italian. Brother of Benedict VIII.

name: Benedict IX
text: Italian; 1st Term.

name: Sylvester III
text: Italian. Validity of election questioned; considered Anti-Pope; deposed at the Council of Sutri.

name: Benedict IX
text: Italian. 2nd Term; deposed at the Council of Sutri.

name: Gregory VI
text: Italian. Deposed at the Council of Sutri.

name: Clement II
text: German. Appointed by Henry III at the Council of Sutri; crowned Henry III as Holy Roman Emperor.

name: Benedict IX
text: Italian. 3rd Term; deposed and excommunicated.

name: Damasus II
text: German.

name: Leo IX
text: German. In 1054, mutual excommunications of Leo IX and Patriarch of Constantinople Michael I Cerularius began the East–West Schism. The anathematizations were rescinded by Pope Paul VI and Patriarch Athenagoras in 1965.[13]

name: Victor II
text: German.

name: Stephen IX
text: German. Sometimes called Stephen X. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Nicholas II
text: French. In 1059 the College of Cardinals was designated the sole body of pope electors in the document In nomine Domini. (Papal conclave).

name: Alexander II
text: Italian. Authorised the Norman conquest of England in 1066.

name: Gregory VII
text: Italian. Initiated the Gregorian Reforms. Restricted the use of the title "Papa" to the Bishop of Rome.[4] Member of the Order of Saint Benedict. Political struggle with German Emperor Henry IV, who had to go to Canossa (1077).

name: Victor III
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict. Called the Synod of Benevento (1087) condemning lay investiture.

name: Urban II
text: French. Preached and started the First Crusade. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Paschal II
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict. Ordered the building of the basilica of Santi Quattro Coronati.

name: Gelasius II
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict.

name: Callixtus II
text: French. Opened the First Council of the Lateran in 1123

name: Honorius II
text: Italian. Canon Regular of S. Maria di San Reno. Approved the new military order of the Knights Templar in 1128.

name: Innocent II
text: Italian. Canon Regular of Lateran; Convened the Second Council of the Lateran, 1139

name: Celestine II
text: Italian.

name: Lucius II
text: Italian. Canon Regular of S. Frediano di Lucca.

name: Eugene III
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Cistercians. Announced the Second Crusade.

name: Anastasius IV
text: Italian.

name: Adrian IV
text: First and only English pope; purportedly granted Ireland to Henry II, King of England. Canon Regular of St. Rufus Monastery .

name: Alexander III
text: Italian. Convened the Third Council of the Lateran, 1179.

name: Lucius III
text: Italian.

name: Urban III
text: Italian.

name: Gregory VIII
text: Italian. Canon Regular Premostratense. Proposed the Third Crusade.

name: Clement III
text: Italian.

name: Celestine III
text: Motto: Perfice gressus meos in semitis tuis ("Going in Thy path")

name: Innocent III
text: Italian. Convened the Fourth Council of the Lateran, 1215. Initiated the Fourth Crusade but later distanced himself from it and threatened participants with excommunication when it became clear that the leadership abandoned a focus on conquest of the Holy Land and instead intended to sack Christian cities.[16]Endorsed the Franciscan Order.

name: Honorius III
text: Italian. Initiated the Fifth Crusade. Approved several religious and tertiary orders.

name: Gregory IX
text: Italian. Canonized Elisabeth of Hungary (1235). Initiated the Inquisition in France and endorsed the Northern Crusades.

name: Celestine IV
text: Italian. Died before coronation.

name: Innocent IV
text: Italian. Convened the First Council of Lyons (1245). Issued the bull Ad extirpanda that permitted the torture of heretics (1252).

name: Alexander IV
text: Italian. Established an Inquisition in France.

name: Urban IV
text: French. Instituted the feast of Corpus Christi (1264).

name: Clement IV
text: French.

name: Gregory X
text: Italian. Convened the Second Council of Lyons (1274). Responsible for regulation all papal conclaves until the 20th century.

name: Innocent V
text: French. Member of the Dominican Order.

name: Adrian V
text:
Italian. Annulled Gregory X's papal bull on the regulations of
                                papal conclaves.

name: John XXI
text: Portuguese. Due to a confusion over the numbering of popes named John in the 13th century, there was no John XX. There has never been a John XX, because the 20th pope of this name formerly when elected, decided to skip the number XX and be counted as John XXI instead. He wanted to correct what in his time was believed to be an error in the counting of his predecessors John XV to XIX

name: Nicholas III
text: Italian. Planned the Sicilian Vespers.

name: Martin IV
text: French.

name: Honorius IV
text: Italian.

name: Nicholas IV
text: Italian. Member of the Franciscan Order.

name: Celestine V
text: Italian. One of the few popes who resigned voluntarily. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict. Founded the Celestines. Resigned from office and rumored to have been murdered in prison by Boniface VIII.

name: Boniface VIII
text: Italian. Formalized the Jubilee in 1300. Issued Unam Sanctam (1302) which proclaimed papal supremacy and pushing it to its historical extreme.

name: Benedict XI
text:
Motto: Illustra faciem Tuam super servum Tuum ("Let Your Face shine upon Your servant")

Italian. Member of the Dominican Order. Reverted Boniface VIII's Unam Sanctam.

name: Clement V
text: French. Pope at Avignon. Convened the Council of Vienne (1311–1312). Initiated the persecution of the Knights Templar with the bull Pastoralis Praeeminentiae under pressure from King Philip IV of France.

name: John XXII
text: French. Pope at Avignon. Controversial for his views on the Beatific Vision.

name: Benedict XII
text: French. Pope at Avignon. Member of the Order of Cistercians. Known for issuing the Apostolic constitution Benedictus Deus (1336).

name: Clement VI
text: French. Pope at Avignon. Reigned during the Black Death and absolved those who died of it of their sins.

name: Innocent VI
text: French. Pope at Avignon. Through his exertions the Treaty of Brétigny (1360) was brought about.

name: Urban V
text: French. Pope at Avignon. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict. Reformed areas of education and sent missionary movements across Europe and Asia. His pontificate witnessed the Alexandrian and Savoyard crusades.

name: Gregory XI
text: French. Pope at Avignon; returns to Rome. The last French pope.

name: Urban VI
text: Italian. Western Schism. Last pontiff to be elected outside the College of Cardinals.

name: Boniface IX
text: Italian. Western Schism.

name: Innocent VII
text: Italian. Western Schism.

name: Gregory XII
text: Italian. Western Schism.

name: Martin V
text: Italian. Convened the Council of Basel (1431). Initiated the Hussite Wars.

name: Eugene IV
text: Italian. Member of the Augustinian Order. Nephew of Martin V. Crowned Sigismund emperor at Rome in 1433. Transferred the Council of Basel to Ferrara. It was later transferred again, to Florence, because of the Bubonic plague.

name: Nicholas V
text: Italian. Member of the Dominican Order. Held the Jubilee of 1450. Crowned Frederick III emperor at Rome (1452). Issued the Papal Bull Dum Diversas allowing Portugal's right to conquer and subjugate Saracens and pagans (1452). Created a library in the Vatican which would eventually become the Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana.

name: Callixtus III
text: The first Spanish pope. Ordered the Feast of the Transfiguration to be celebrated on 6 August. Ordered the retrial of Joan of Arc, in which she was vindicated.

name: Pius II
text: Italian. Displayed a great interest in urban planning. Founded Pienza near Siena as the ideal city in 1462. Known for his work on the Commentaries.

name: Paul II
text: Italian. The nephew of Eugene IV. Built the Palazzo San Marco (now Palazzo Venezia). Approved the introduction of printing in the Papal States.

name: Sixtus IV
text: Italian. Member of the Franciscan Order. Commissioned the Sistine Chapel. Authorized an Inquisition targeting converted Jewish Christians in Spain at the request of Queen Isabella and King Ferdinand.

name: Innocent VIII
text: Italian. Appointed Tomás de Torquemada. Endorsed the prosecution of witchcraft in the bull Summis desiderantes affectibus (1484).

name: Alexander VI
text: Spanish; Nephew of Callixtus III; father to Cesare Borgia and Lucrezia Borgia. Divided the extra-European world between Spain and Portugal in the bull Inter caetera (1493). No Alexander V due to the antipope.

name: Pius III
text: Italian. Nephew of Pius II. Founded the Piccolomini Library adjoining the Siena Cathedral.

name: Julius II
text: Italian. Nephew of Sixtus IV; convened the Fifth Council of the Lateran (1512). Took control of all the Papal States for the first time. Commissioned Michelangelo to paint the Sistine Chapel ceiling. Proposed plans for rebuilding St Peter's Basilica.

name: Leo X
text: Italian. Son of Lorenzo the Magnificent. Closed the Fifth Council of the Lateran. Remembered for granting indulgences to those who donated to rebuild St. Peter's Basilica; excommunicated Martin Luther (1521). Extended the Spanish Inquisition into Portugal.

name: Adrian VI
text:
Motto: Patere et sustine ("Respect and wait")[17]

The only Dutch pope; last non-Italian to be elected pope until John Paul II in 1978. Tutor of Emperor Charles V. Retained his baptismal name as his regnal name.

name: Clement VII
text:
Motto: Candor illæsus ("Unharmed candor")[18]

Italian; Cousin of Leo X. Rome plundered by imperial troops (1527). Forbade the divorce of Henry VIII; crowned Charles V as emperor at Bologna (1530). His niece was married to the future Henry II of France. Ordered Michelangelo's painting of The Last Judgment in the Sistine Chapel.

name: Paul III
text: Italian. Opened the Council of Trent (1545). His illegitimate son became the first Duke of Parma. Decreed the second and final excommunication of Henry VIII. Appointed Michelangelo to supervise construction of St. Peter's Basilica (1546).

name: Julius III
text: Italian. Established the Collegium Germanicum (1552). Reconvened the Council of Trent. The Innocenzo Scandal.

name: Marcellus II
text: Italian. The last to use his birth name as the regnal name. Instituted immediate economies in Vatican expenditures. The Missa Papae Marcelli composed in his honour.

name: Paul IV
text:
Motto: Dominus mihi adjutor ("The Lord is my helper")[19]

Italian. Member of the Theatines. Established the Roman Ghetto in Cum Nimis Absurdum (1555) and established the Index of Forbidden Books. Ordered Michelangelo to repaint the nudes of The Last Judgment modestly.

name: Pius IV
text: Italian. Reopened and closed the Council of Trent. Ordered public construction to improve the water supply of Rome. Instituted the Tridentine Creed.

name: Pius V
text:
Motto: Utinam dirigantur viæ meæ ad custodiendas ("It binds us to keep")[20]

Italian. Member of the Dominican Order. Excommunicated Elizabeth I (1570). Battle of Lepanto (1571); instituted the feast of Our Lady of Victory. Issued the 1570 Roman Missal.

name: Gregory XIII
text:
Motto: Aperuit et clausit ("Opened and closed")[21]

Italian. Reformed the calendar (1582); built the Gregorian Chapel in the Vatican. The first pope to bestow the Immaculate Conception as Patroness to the Philippine Islands through the bull Ilius Fulti Præsido (1579). Strengthened diplomatic ties with Asian nations.

name: Sixtus V
text: Italian. Member of the Conventual Franciscan Order. Known for fixing and completing building works to major basilicas in Rome. Limited the College of Cardinals to 70 in number; doubled the number of curial congregations.

name: Urban VII
text:
Italian; Supported by the Spanish. Shortest-reigning pope; died
                                before coronation. Set the first known worldwide smoking ban, banning smoking in and
                                near all churches.

name: Gregory XIV
text: Italian. Modified the constitution Effraenatam of Sixtus V so that the penalty for abortion did not apply until the foetus became animated (1591). Made gambling on papal elections punishable by excommunication.

name: Innocent IX
text: Italian. Supported the cause of Philip II and the Catholic League against Henry IV in the French Wars of Religion. Prohibited the alienation of church property.

name: Clement VIII
text: Italian. Initiated an alliance of European Christian powers to partake in the war with the Ottoman Empire known as The Long War (1595). Convened the Congregatio de Auxiliis which addressed doctrinal disputes between the Dominicans and Jesuits regarding free will and divine grace.[22]

name: Leo XI
text: Italian. The nephew of Leo X. Called "Papa Lampo" (Lightning Pope) for his brief pontificate.

name: Paul V
text:
Motto: Absit nisi in te gloriari ("May it be absent, except to glory in you")[23]

Italian. Known for various building projects which included the facade of St Peter's Basilica. Established the Bank of the Holy Spirit (1605); restored the Aqua Traiana.

name: Gregory XV
text: Italian. Established the Congregation for the Propagation of the Faith (1622). Issued the bull Aeterni Patris (1621) which imposed conclaves to be by secret ballot. Issued the constitution Omnipotentis Dei against magicians and witches (1623).

name: Urban VIII
text: Italian. Trial against Galileo Galilei. The last pope to expand papal territory by force of arms. Issued a 1624 bull that made the use of tobacco in holy places punishable by excommunication.

name: Innocent X
text:
Motto: Alleviatæ sunt aquæ super terram ("Water on earth")[24]

Italian. The great-great-great-grandson of Alexander VI. Erected the Fontana dei Quattro Fiumi in Piazza Navona. Promulgated the apostolic constitution Cum occasione (1653) which condemned five doctrines of Jansenism as heresy.

name: Alexander VII
text: Italian. Great-nephew of Paul V. Commissioned St. Peter's Square. Issued the constitution Sollicitudo Omnium Ecclesiarum that set the doctrine of the Immaculate Conception almost identical to that of Pius IX centuries later.

name: Clement IX
text:
Motto: Aliis non sibi Clemens ("Clement to others, not to himself")[25]

Italian. Commissioned the colonnade of St. Peter's Square. Mediated in the peace of Aachen (1668).

name: Clement X
text:
Bonum auget malum minuit ("He increases good and diminishes evil")[26]

Italian. Canonized the first saint from the Americas: St. Rose of Lima (1671). Decorated the bridge of Sant' Angelo with the ten statues of angels and the two fountains that adorn the piazza of St. Peter's. Established regulations for the removal of relics of saints from cemeteries.

name: Innocent XI
text:
Motto: Avarus non Implebitur ("The covetous man is not satisfied")[27]

Italian. Condemned the doctrine of mental reservation (1679) and initiated the Holy League. Extended the Holy Name of Mary as a universal feast (1684). Admired for positive contributions to catechesis.

name: Alexander VIII
text: Italian. Condemned the so-called philosophical sin (1690).

name: Innocent XII
text: Italian. Issued the bull Romanum decet Pontificem to stop nepotism (1692). Erected various charitable and educational institutions.

name: Clement XI
text: Italian. The "Chinese Rites" controversy. Patronized the first archaeological excavations in the Roman catacombs and made the feast of the Immaculate Conception universal.[12]

name: Innocent XIII
text: Italian. Prohibited the Jesuits from prosecuting their mission in China ordering that no new members should be received into the order.

name: Benedict XIII
text: Italian. Member of the Dominican Order; third and last member of the Orsini family to be pope. Originally called Benedict XIV due to the antipope but reverted to XIII. Repealed the worldwide tobacco smoking ban set by Urban VII and Urban VIII.

name: Clement XII
text:
Motto: Dabis discernere inter malum et bonum ("You shall deign to distinguish between good and evil")[28]

Italian. [Completed the new façade of the Archbasilica of St. John Lateran (1735). Commissioned the Trevi Fountain in Rome (1732). Condemned Freemasonry in In eminenti apostolatus (1738). Last pope to be elected at an old age until Pope Benedict XVI in 2005.

name: Benedict XIV
text:
Motto: Curabuntur omnes ("All will be healed")[29]

Italian. Reformed the education of priests and the calendar of feasts. Completed the Trevi Fountain and affirmed the teachings of Thomas Aquinas; founded academies of art, religion and science.

name: Clement XIII
text: Italian. Provided the famous fig leaves on nude male statues in the Vatican. Defended the Society of Jesus in "Apostolicum pascendi" (1765).

name: Clement XIV
text: Italian. Member of the Conventual Franciscan Order. Suppressed the Society of Jesus in the brief "Dominus ac Redemptor" (1773).

name: Pius VI
text:
Motto: Floret in domo domini ("It blossoms in the house of God")[30]

Italian. Condemned the French Revolution; expelled from the Papal States by French troops from 1798 until his death. The last pope to be a patron of Renaissance art.

name: Pius VII
text: Italian. Member of the Order of Saint Benedict. Present at Napoleon's coronation as Emperor of the French. Briefly expelled from the Papal States by the French between 1809 and 1814.

name: Leo XII
text: Italian. Placed the Catholic educational system under the control of the Jesuits through Quod divina sapientia (1824). Condemned the Bible societies.

name: Pius VIII
text: Italian. Accepted Louis Philippe I as King of the French. Condemned the masonic secret societies and modernist biblical translations in the brief Litteris altero (1830).

name: Gregory XVI
text: Italian. Member of the Camaldolese Order; last non-bishop to be elected to the papacy. Opposed democratic and modernising reforms in the Papal States.

name: Pius IX
text: Italian. Opened the First Vatican Council; lost the Papal States to Italy. Defined the dogma of the Immaculate Conception and defined papal infallibility. Issued the controversial Syllabus of Errors. Second longest serving pope in history after Saint Peter.

name: Leo XIII
text: Italian. Issued the encyclical Rerum novarum; supported Christian democracy against Communism. Had the fourth-longest reign after Pius IX, Saint Peter and John Paul II. Promoted the rosary and the scapular and approved two new Marian scapulars; first pope to fully embrace the concept of Mary as mediatrix.

name: Pius X
text:
Motto: Instaurare Omnia in Christo ("Restore all things in Christ")

Italian. Encouraged and expanded reception of the Eucharist. Combatted Modernism; issued the oath against it. Advocated the Gregorian Chant and reformed the Roman Breviary.

name: Benedict XV
text:
Motto: In te, Domine, speravi: non confundar in aeternum. ("In thee, o Lord, have I trusted: let me not be confounded for evermore.")

Italian. Credited for intervening for peace during World War I. Issued the 1917 Code of Canon Law; supported the missionaries in Maximum Illud. Remembered by Benedict XVI as a "prophet of peace".

name: Pius XI
text:
Motto: Pax Christi in Regno Christi ("The Peace of Christ in the Kingdom of Christ")

Italian. Signed the Lateran Treaty with Italy (1929) establishing Vatican City as a sovereign state. Inaugurated Vatican Radio (1931). Re-founded the Pontifical Academy of Sciences (1936). Created the feast of Christ the King. Opposed Communism and Nazism.

name: Pius XII
text:
Motto: Opus Justitiae Pax ("The work of justice [shall be] peace")

Italian. Invoked papal infallibility in the encyclical Munificentissimus Deus; defined the dogma of the Assumption. Eliminated the Italian majority of cardinals. Credited with intervening for peace during World War II; controversial for his reactions to the Holocaust.

name: John XXIII
text:
Motto: Obedientia et Pax ("Obedience and peace")

Italian. Opened the Second Vatican Council; called "Good Pope John". Issued the encyclical Pacem in terris (1963) on peace and nuclear disarmament; intervened for peace during the Cuban Missile Crisis (1962).

name: Paul VI
text:
Motto: Cum Ipso in Monte ("With Him on the mount")

Italian. Last pope to be crowned in a coronation with the tiara. First pope to travel to the United States and Australia; first pope since 1809 to travel outside Italy. Closed the Second Vatican Council. Issued the encyclical Humanae vitae (1968) condemning artificial contraception.

name: John Paul I
text:
Motto: Humilitas ("Humility")

Italian. Abolished the coronation opting for the Papal Inauguration. First pope to use 'the First' in papal name; first with two names for two immediate predecessors. Last pope to use the Sedia Gestatoria.

name: John Paul II
text:
Motto: Totus Tuus ("Totally yours")

First Polish pope and first non-Italian pope since Adrian VI (1522–1523). Traveled extensively, visiting 129 countries during his pontificate. Third longest reign after Pius IX and Saint Peter. Founded World Youth Day (1984) and the Pontifical Academy of Social Sciences (1994). Canonized more saints than all his predecessors. Youngest individual to start his papacy since Pius IX (1846).

name: Benedict XVI
text:
Motto: Cooperatores Veritatis ("Cooperators of the truth")

German. Oldest to become pope since Clement XII (1730). Elevated the Tridentine Mass to a more prominent position and promoted the use of Latin; re-introduced several disused papal garments. Established the Anglican Ordinariate (2009). First pope to renounce the papacy on his own initiative since Celestine V (1294),[32] retaining regnal name with title of Pope Emeritus.[33]

name: Francis
text:
Motto: Miserando atque Eligendo ("Lowly but chosen", literally 'by having mercy, by choosing him')[34]

Argentinian. First pope to be born outside Europe since Gregory III (731–741) and the first from the Americas; first pope from the Southern Hemisphere. First pope from a religious institute since Gregory XVI (1831–1846); first Jesuit pope. First to use a new and non-composed regnal name since Lando (913–914).
